#Authority & Responsibility

This section explains who authorises automated systems and who is responsible for their outcomes.

Entries describe the roles, responsibilities and decision structures that determine who approves a system, who defines its purpose and who answers for its actions when decisions are questioned.

Authority and responsibility are central to governance because automated systems do not remove accountability. When a decision causes harm, regulators, investigators or courts will ask who authorised the system and who was responsible for its operation.

This section focuses on organisational responsibility structures. It does not examine the technical behaviour of systems or the records used to explain their decisions.
